1) YOUR STANDARD BASIC COMMIT PROCESS IS AS FOLLOWS  :

i) To list all remote repositories that are currently connected to your local repository
$ git remote -v

ii) To check status 
$ git status

iii) To add a change in the working directory to the staging area: 
$ git add .

iv) To save changes to the local repository (Using the "git commit" command only saves a new commit object in the local Git repository.)
$git commit -m"message here about what's in this commit"

v) To upload local repository content to a remote repository:
$git push origin master

========================================================================================================
========================================================================================================
2) TO CREATE A NEW BRANCH
$git branch new-branch-name

========================================================================================================
========================================================================================================
3) TO CHANGE FROM THE CURRENT BRANCH YOU'RE WORKING ON TO WORKING ON A NEW BRANCH
$git checkout new-branch-name

(you will be able to see that the branch you're working on has changed because it's shown in 
brackets at the end of the file address)

========================================================================================================
========================================================================================================
4) TO CLONE A REPOSITORY

https://stackabuse.com/git-clone-a-repository/

Cloning Repositories
In order to clone a remote repository you'll want to use the git clone command, which is 
typically used in this fashion:

$ git clone <repo-url>

This will clone the repository in to your current working directory using as the destination directory 
the name of the repo. In order to clone it in to a different directory, you can specify one as the 
second parameter to clone:

$ git clone <repo-url> <directory>

An example of this command for a public GitHub repo would look like the following:

$ git clone git@github.com:scottwrobinson/twentyjs.git twentyjs-clone
Cloning into 'twentyjs-clone'...
remote: Enumerating objects: 48, done.
remote: Total 48 (delta 0), reused 0 (delta 0), pack-reused 48
Receiving objects: 100% (48/48), 9.35 KiB | 0 bytes/s, done.
Resolving deltas: 100% (22/22), done.

========================================================================================================
========================================================================================================
5) TO CHANGE THE REMOTE REPOSITORY (that changes will be "pushed" to). 

If you've successfully cloned a repository onto your machine, and want to change the repository that 
your subsequent "git pushes" push changes to (to one that you own), then you'll need to change the remote 
repository.

You will first need to create new repository (I think that the ONLY way to do this is to go into 
github and click the "create repository" button, I don't think you can do it from git bash command 
line).

When you've done this, and got the link to your new repository (which will look something like this 
https://github.com/peter-lancaster/freecodecamp-npm-challenges.git) then use the git remote set-url 
command followed by the remote name, and the remoteâ€™s URL:

$git remote set-url <remote-name> <remote-url>

example:

$git remote set-url origin https://github.com/peter-lancaster/freecodecamp-npm-challenges.git

